  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 유자(劉子) : '
    value: 원(元)나라의 유기(劉祁). 《귀잠지(歸潛志)》라는 책을 썼는데, 여기에 나오는 천인상승(天人相勝)에 대한 말은 이 책에 있다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 태공(太公) : '
    value: 주 문왕(周文王)의 신하인 여상(呂尙)이 80살까지 은거하여 있다가, 위수(渭水)에서 낚시질을 하는 중에 문왕을 만났다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 주매신(朱買臣) : '
    value: 한(漢)나라 무제(武帝) 때의 사람. 집이 가난하여 나무를 해다 팔아가며 생활을 하다가 50살이 지나서 처음으로 추천을 받아 회계태수(會稽太守)가 되었다.
english:
  title: On the Struggle Between Heaven and Man
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Liu Zi once said, "When men unite, they overcome Heaven; yet when Heaven ordains, it too can overcome men." I have long held this teaching true, and now I believe it more than ever. Why is this? When I served as keeper of records at Wansan, envious colleagues slandered me and I was dismissed. Upon arriving at court, that very man remained in positions of influence, wielding his honeyed tongue to bar my way. For nine long years I found no advancement—this was man triumphing over Heaven, not Heaven's will at all. But when that man finally passed away, in that very year I entered the Academy of Letters, and through successive offices of trust, I rose swiftly to high rank. This was Heaven triumphing over man. Can mortal scheming truly prevail forever?

    Some challenged me, saying, "The Duke of Qi met King Wen at eighty, and Zhu MaiChen rose to honor at fifty. Were these not cases of slander causing delayed fortune? Surely it was destiny alone." I replied, "Their late fortune came as you say, through fate's decree. Yet examining my own circumstances: even in that dark hour, my destiny was not utterly ruined—it was the villain's calculated ambition that magnified my suffering." Another objected, "But if fate was not yet severely adverse, and the villain's schemes merely accelerated it, is that not also destiny?" I answered, "Had I but shown patience then and not given him grievance, such ruin would never have come to pass. I myself invited this calamity through my own actions—how then can this be attributed to Heaven's will?"

    Hearing this, others came to accept my meaning, saying, "If you repent so deeply of your errors, surely you were destined to reach the highest stations."
  footnotes:
    - Liu Zi (Liu Qi of Yuan) was a Yuan dynasty scholar who wrote the Guiqianzhi (Records of Returning to Quietude), which contains the teaching on the mutual triumph of Heaven and man.
    - The Duke of Qi (Lü Shang) lived in reclusion until age eighty before meeting King Wen of Zhou while fishing at the Wei River.
    - Zhu MaiChen was a Han dynasty figure who, despite poverty and years of collecting firewood for sale, first gained official advancement at fifty, becoming governor of Kuaiji.
